Phenomic Selection Workshop - practicals

R Rincent & V Segura

2022/09/20

The aim of this practical is to perform phenomic predictions in bread wheat using NIRS measured on grains and to further compare phenomic prediction with genomic prediction. Data come from Rincent et al.(2018).

Packages installation and loading

install.packages(c("prospectr", "signal", "rrBLUP", "sommer"))
library(prospectr)
library(signal)
library(rrBLUP)

Filters on genomic data and computation of kinship matrix

MAF filtering

p <- rowMeans(geno)
summary(p)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## 0.006696 0.319196 0.602679 0.573041 0.853940 0.993304
ToRemove <- which(p <= 0.025 | p >= 0.975)
length(ToRemove)
## [1] 835
geno <- geno[-ToRemove, ]
dim(geno)
## [1] 9698  224

Compute kinship

p <- rowMeans(geno)
q <- 1-p
genot.ok <- 2*t(geno)
rm(geno)
genot.scaled <- scale(genot.ok, center = 2*p, scale = sqrt(4*p*q))
matA1 <- tcrossprod(genot.scaled) / ncol(genot.scaled)
rm(p, q, genot.scaled, ToRemove)

Are the spectra under genetic determinism ?

Here we fit a GBLUP model to each wavelength to estimate the genomic and residual variances along the spectrum. We work with one pre-treatment only: norm_der1.

spec <- spectra$norm_der1$NIRS
GenomicVariance <- ResidualVariance <- rep(NA, nrow(spec))
for (i in 1:nrow(spec)) {
  cat(i)
  mod4 <- mixed.solve(y = spec[i,], K = matA1)
  GenomicVariance[i] <- mod4$Vu
  ResidualVariance[i] <- mod4$Ve
  rm(mod4)
}

Genomic and phenomic predictions

Hyperspectral smilarity matrix

spct <- spectra$norm_der1$NIRS  # Choose a pretreatment
spct2 <- scale(t(spct), center=T, scale=T) # scale absorbance at each wavelength (predictor)
matH <- tcrossprod(spct2)/ncol(spct2) # Compute the hyperspectral similarity matrix
matH[1:5, 1:5]

Cross-validation

Nenvt = 8   # Number of environments
Nind = nrow(pheno) # Number of varieties
Nrep = 25   # Number of repetitions for the cross validation
Nout = 30   # Number of varieties in the predicted set
AccuHBLUP <- AccuGBLUP <- matrix(NA, Nrep, Nenvt)
colnames(AccuHBLUP) <- colnames(AccuGBLUP) <- colnames(pheno)[2:ncol(pheno)]
for (envt in 2:9) {
  print(envt)
  phenotype <- pheno[, envt]
  for (rep in 1:Nrep) {
    valid <- sample(Nind, Nout)
    phenoTrain <- phenotype
    phenoTrain[valid] <- NA
    gblup <- mixed.solve(y=phenoTrain, K=matA1)
    hblup <- mixed.solve(y=phenoTrain, K=matH)
    AccuGBLUP[rep,(envt-1)] <- cor(gblup$u[valid], phenotype[valid], use="complete.obs")
    AccuHBLUP[rep,(envt-1)] <- cor(hblup$u[valid], phenotype[valid], use="complete.obs")
  }
}
